Oppo has launched two new smartphones in South Africa – the A53s and the A15. These smartphones will be available locally from 7 November and will come with full Google Mobile Services. Oppo is the second-biggest smartphone manufacturer in China, it has the largest smartphone market share in Egypt and in South East Asia, and it has seen 102% year-on-year growth in Western Europe. The two smartphones the company has rolled out to South Africa are detailed below. The Oppo A15 has an AI-powered triple camera which includes a 13MP primary camera, a 2MP macro lens, and a 2MP depth camera. It also boasts a 4,230mAh battery, 2GB RAM, and 32GB internal storage. This smartphone also supports HDR and offers 15 photo filters and 10 video filters. The Oppo A15 sports has a 6.42-inch waterdrop display with an 89% screen-to-body ratio and a resolution of 1,600 x 720. “We are glad to introduce OPPO A15, which offers the essential features users need to satisfy their mobile lifestyle,” said Oppo head of GTM operations Liam Faurie. “With OPPO A15, you can take great photos with the AI Triple Camera, enjoy the HD+ display on the 6.52” big screen, all the while enabling you to stay connected with your friends and family.” It will be priced from R2,999 in South Africa. Oppo also announced the A53s, which it said makes premium features accessible to more customers. This smartphone comes with a 90Hz, 6.5-inch HD+ Neo-Display that also offers up to a 120Hz touch sampling rate. It sports 4GB RAM and 128GB storage while packing a 5,000mAh battery. “With the 90Hz Neo-Display, A53s offers a feature found on flagship-level smartphones, but still ensures long-lasting power, a faster performance, and an enhanced user experience that suit their everyday entertainment and communication needs,” said Faurie. The Oppo A53s will be priced from R4,999 in South Africa. Both smartphones are available from a large range of South African retailers including Foschini, Cellucity, 4U, Chatz, Game, Hi, and Vodacom stores. Specifications and photos of the Oppo A15 and Oppo A53s are below. <img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-368493" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Oppo-A15.jpg" alt="Oppo A15" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Oppo-A15.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Oppo-A15-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Oppo-A15-300x202.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter wp-image-373790 size-large" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-640x430.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-640x430.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-300x202.jpg 300w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-768x516.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue-1200x806.jpg 1200w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15-Mystery-Blue.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> <img class="aligncenter wp-image-373792 size-large" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15Image5-640x430.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="430" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15Image5-640x430.jpg 640w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15Image5-595x400.jpg 595w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15Image5-300x202.jpg 300w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/A15Image5-768x516.jpg 768w, h